Title: Fooled by Randomness: The Hidden Role of Chance in Life and in the Markets (Incerto)
Author: Nassim Nicholas Taleb
My Review:
Really good book overall about mathematical intuition of the physical world, sometimes the writer may give vibes of intelectual superiority with regards to common people.

Funny anecdote, philosopher saying there is no society where a majority of the people man have an income higher than the mean income of the population.

Author says it’s absurd and that he means the median, this is correct. Although having into account that in a majority of civilizations income distribution is exponential (Pareto) the philosophers statement becomes trivial.

Title: Liar's Poker
Author: Michael   Lewis
My Review:
Great book describing the experience in the trading floor in the late 80’s.

What if game proposed by Michaels friend on the trading floor is a pretty fun concept to think about. “What if there is a Nuclear Bomb in Chernobyl” “We should sell US potato futures”.

Audiobook with the writers voice makes the listening experience also pretty smooth.
